doc.ContractDescription: IGF::OT::IGF THE PROPOSED INNOVATION IS A POWER CONVERSION TECHNOLOGY THAT WILL HELP ACHIEVE NASA'S FUNDAMENTAL AERONAUTICS PROGRAM (FAP) GOALS OF REDUCING EMISSIONS AND INCREASING FUEL EFFICIENCY FOR HIGH SPEED FLIGHT. NASA'S OBJECTIVE TO INCREASE THE SPECIFIC POWER OF HIGH EFFICIENCY ELECTRIC COMPONENTS IN ORDER TO MAKE A 10 MEGA-WATT ONBOARD POWER GENERATION AND/OR UTILIZATION FEASIBLE FOR PROPULSION REQUIRES THE DEVELOPMENT OF SUB-SCALE TECHNOLOGIES TO SUPPORT THE DEVELOPMENT AND VALIDATION OF NEWER TURBOELECTRIC AIRCRAFT AND EMBEDDED BOUNDARY LAYER ELECTRIC PROPULSION SYSTEMS. COMPACT AND LIGHTWEIGHT TURBINE GENERATORS SCALING FROM THE KW TO MW CLASS ARE NEEDED TO TRANSITION HIGH SPEED AIRCRAFT TO HYBRID ELECTRIC PROPULSION SYSTEMS. METIS DESIGN CORP IS DEVELOPING A LIGHTWEIGHT, COMPACT, GAS TURBINE GENERATOR THAT DRAWS ON RECENT INNOVATIONS IN THE FIELDS OF PERMANENT MAGNET GENERATORS AND TURBOMACHINERY, TO ACHIEVE A TARGET POWER DENSITY OF OVER TWICE THE STATE-OF-THE-ART AND THE POTENTIAL TO SCALE TO 100'S OF KW. THE PROPOSED TURBINE ENGINE USES A LIGHTWEIGHT, TWO-SPOOL CONFIGURATION THAT ELIMINATES THE NEED FOR THE HEAVY REDUCTION GEARBOX REQUIRED BY STATE-OF-THE-ART SYSTEMS. PHASE II OF THIS SBIR EFFORT WILL DEVELOP A DETAILED DESIGN, THEN FABRICATE AND TEST THE COMPLETE TURBINE GENERATO SUB-SYSTEM IN A LABORATORY ENVIRONMENT.

doc.ContractDescription: UNDERSTANDING THE FORMATION AND EVOLUTION OF THE MILKY WAY GALAXY IS A FUNDAMENTAL UNSOLVED PROBLEM IN ASTROPHYSICS. OUR GALAXY OFFERS BY FAR THE BEST CHANCE TO STUDY A GALACTIC SYSTEM IN GREAT DETAIL AND HENCE TO LEARN AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE REGARDING THE FORMATION OF ITS STRUCTURAL COMPONENTS AND ALSO, ON A SMALLER SCALE, HOW GAS IS CONVERTED TO STARS AND HOW STARS MIGRATE AROUND AND WITHIN THE GALAXY. A BASIC QUESTION IS HOW STARS FORM, AT WHAT RATES, AND IN WHAT TYPES OF AGGREGATES. THIS CAN BE OBSERVED DIRECTLY ONLY AT THE PRESENT TIME. IN ORDER TO UNDERSTAND WHAT HAPPENED IN THE MILKY WAY AT EARLIER EPOCHS WE MUST STUDY THE FOSSIL RECORD. DESPITE ITS IMPORTANCE, RECONSTRUCTING DISRUPTED STAR CLUSTERS IS PROVED TO BE CHALLENGING BECAUSE INDIVIDUAL STAR CLUSTERS DISSOLVE QUICKLY UPON THEIR FORMATION. FORTUNATELY, STARS THAT WERE BORN FROM THE SAME BIRTH CLOUD WILL SHARE SIMILAR ELEMENTAL ABUNDANCES. THEREFORE, THE ELEMENTAL ABUNDANCES OF EACH STAR COULD WORK AS UNIQUE IDENTIFIERS OF THEIR BIRTH CLOUD, EVEN FOR STARS THAT SUBSEQUENTLY MIGRATE FAR FROM THEIR BIRTH CLOUDS. BY SEARCHING FOR COLLECTIONS OF STARS AT THE SAME POINT IN ELEMENTAL ABUNDANCE SPACE, ONE MAY BE ABLE TO RECONSTRUCT STAR CLUSTERS THAT ARE NOW DYNAMICALLY DISPERSED THROUGH THEIR CHEMICAL SIGNATURES, AN IDEA KNOWN AS "CHEMICAL TAGGING". THIS TECHNIQUE WILL SHED LIGHT ON HOW STARS FORM, IN PARTICULAR THE EXTENT TO WHICH STARS FORM IN SMALL OR MASSIVE CLUSTERS OF STARS (WHAT IS KNOWN AS THE CLUSTER MASS FUNCTION, OR CMF). DETECTING THE MOST MASSIVE CLUSTERS IN THE FOSSIL RECORD WOULD NOT ONLY SHED LIGHT ON HOW STARS FORM BUT WOULD ALSO PROVIDE NOVEL INSIGHT INTO THE EVOLUTION OF THE GRAVITATIONAL POTENTIAL OF THE MILKY WAY AS IT IS THE LATTER THAT SETS THE MAXIMUM FRAGMENTATION MASS IN GALACTIC SYSTEM. DESPITE ALL THESE PROMISING PROSPECTS OF CHEMICAL TAGGING, THE STUDIES ON FORWARD MODELING THE CHEMICAL TAGGING DETECTION REMAIN SCARCE. IT IS UNCLEAR WHETHER WE COULD GATHER ENOUGH STARS FROM THE SAME CLUSTER IN THE SOLAR NEIGHBORHOOD AND HOW MASSIVE A STAR CLUSTER HAS TO BE IN ORDER TO BE DETECTED THROUGH CHEMICAL TAGGING. TO FILL IN THIS GAP, WE HAVE CONSTRUCTED A NEW MODEL THAT DIRECTLY INCORPORATES MANY OF THE KEY PROCESSES RELEVANT FOR EVALUATING THE CHEMICAL TAGGING TECHNIQUE. WE HAVE MODELED THE STAR FORMATION HISTORY, THE GAS MASS DISTRIBUTION, THE STELLAR MASS. WITH OUR CURRENT MODEL, WE HAVE DEMONSTRATED (A) THE NECESSITY OF USING MODELS IN ORDER TO INTERPRET THE UPCOMING SURVEY DATA; (B) MORE IMPORTANTLY, OUR MODEL PREDICTS THAT ONGOING SURVEYS SHOULD HAVE ENOUGH STATISTICS TO RECONSTRUCT THE MILKY WAY CMF'S EVOLUTION VIA CHEMICAL TAGGING.
